“Hypothesis 1”

friends_vs_happiness <- select(responses, Number.of.friends, Happiness.in.life) %>% arrange(desc(Number.of.friends))
head(friends_vs_happiness)
##   Number.of.friends Happiness.in.life
## 1                 5                 5
## 2                 5                 5
## 3                 5                 4
## 4                 5                 4
## 5                 5                 4
## 6                 5                 2
#mplot(friends_vs_happiness)
 xyplot( Number.of.friends ~ Happiness.in.life, data = friends_vs_happiness, main="", jitter.x=TRUE, jitter.y=TRUE)

There doesnt seem to be any linear relatinoship between the two variables. However, people most people have a number of friends of 3 or 4 show a happiness of 3 or 4.

“Hypothesis 2”

gender_vs_happiness <- select(responses, Gender, Happiness.in.life)%>%na.omit(gender_vs_happiness)
head(gender_vs_happiness)
##   Gender Happiness.in.life
## 1 female                 4
## 2 female                 4
## 3 female                 4
## 4 female                 2
## 5 female                 3
## 6   male                 3
#mplot(gender_vs_happiness)
bwplot( Happiness.in.life ~ Gender, data = gender_vs_happiness, main="")

both categories have a similar happiness.in.life rating. No correlation between the two variables.

“Hypothesis 3”

happiness_vs_age <- select(responses, Age, Happiness.in.life)%>%na.omit(happiness_vs_age)%>%group_by(Age)%>%summarise(avg_Happiness.in.life = mean(Happiness.in.life)) 
head(happiness_vs_age)
## # A tibble: 6 <U+00D7> 2
##     Age avg_Happiness.in.life
##   <int>                 <dbl>
## 1    15              3.600000
## 2    16              3.379310
## 3    17              3.566038
## 4    18              3.747967
## 5    19              3.765550
## 6    20              3.726804
#mplot(happiness_vs_age)
 xyplot( avg_Happiness.in.life ~ Age, data = happiness_vs_age, main="")

There is no relationship between the two variables.

Data Analysis Hypothesis 1: Relation between Music and Education.

music_vs_education <- select(responses, Music, Education)%>%na.omit(music_vs_education)%>%arrange(Education)
head(music_vs_education)
##   Music               Education
## 1     5                        
## 2     5 college/bachelor degree
## 3     4 college/bachelor degree
## 4     5 college/bachelor degree
## 5     5 college/bachelor degree
## 6     5 college/bachelor degree
#mplot(music_vs_education)
xyplot( Music ~ Education, data = music_vs_education, main="", jitter.x=TRUE, jitter.y=TRUE)

People who have a college degree and secondary degree show very strong music preferences than other categories.
